ce:section.ce:para:
To determine the antimicrobial potential of the nanomaterials, PDT experiments against E. coli were performed with a 670-nm laser at 3 min exposure time. The effects of photoexcited nanomaterial–AbLPS-treated E. coli (OD600: 0.05) on viability were determined. The results indicated no bactericidal effects on E. coli alone with or without laser exposure, and no bactericidal effects on the panel of nanomaterial-treated bacteria without laser treatment (Fig. 4
                     ). However, the N-GQD (5.1%) efficiently exerted an antibacterial effect, resulting in 100% elimination after a 3-min exposure. Moreover, we aimed to determine whether the N-bonding composition affected bacterial viability. Identical photoexcitation experiments indicated a lower N-bonding N-GQD composition of approximately 2.9% in the N 1–C 1s, as well as a reduced bactericidal effect compared with that of N-GQD (5.1%), as shown in Fig. 4. A 24% viability of N-GQD (2.9%)–AbLPS-treated E. coli was observed after 3 min laser irradiation exposure. The results also indicated that regardless of N-GQD type, N 1–C 1s at ratios of both 5.1% and 2.9% eliminated bacteria, evidencing that their bactericidal effects on E. coli were more effective than those of GQD–AbLPS (52% in bacterial viability) with the same treatment procedure. Although the higher N-bonding composition of the N-GQDs generated more ROS than did that of the lower and N-free GQDs, the false positive signals of ROS might have resulted from the interactions among the GQD-based nanomaterials, SOSG reagent, t-MVP, and XTT, compromising the PDT results [31]. The amount of 1O2 and O2

                     − generated from the laser-irradiated nanomaterial–AbLPS-treated E. coli was recorded (Fig. 5
                     ). The generated ROS from the N-GQDs (5.1%)–AbLPS-treated E. coli was more than the amount by the GQD–AbLPS-treated E. coli. Furthermore, the generated ROS clearly decreased as E. coli was treated with nanomaterials alone (without coating Ab) (SI, Fig. S8), demonstrating that the AbLPS antibody was successfully coated with nanomaterials, enhancing its specificity and selectivity. In addition, the results clearly indicated that the three GQD-based nanomaterial–AbLPS antibodies were capable of generating 1O2 and O2

                     − through laser exposure to facilitate PDT, and that this was not caused by the interactions between the nanomaterials and the reagent, which presented similar trends to those shown in Fig. 3 and Tables S1–S3 (SI), indicating that the ROS signal was produced to eliminate bacteria. Moreover, the human squamous carcinoma A431 cells and human peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMC) were also treated by the three GQD-based nanomaterials through PDT (SI, Fig. S9-S11). The photothermal effects of the three GQD-based nanomaterials were not observed following identical laser treatments of the nanomaterial-treated bacteria (SI, Fig. S12). On the basis of these results, it was determined that N atoms are capable of replacing C atoms (the doping atoms) in sp2-bonded molecular systems, resulting in heterocyclic aromatic compounds; this constitutes an effective method for modifying the intrinsic properties of C-based nanomaterials, such as electronic features as well as local and surface chemical characteristics [32]. Therefore, regarding the N-GQD-exhibiting extraordinary quantum confinement and edge effects, the chemical composition of N-GQDs can be changed, exhibiting enhanced photochemical, electrochemical, and electrocatalytic activities and further providing advantages in biomedical and optoelectronic applications [14]. Furthermore, the increase in ROS caused by the N-GQDs with a ratio of 5.1% might have been caused by the increased intersystem crossing and increased triplet state yield of N-GQDs with a ratio of 5.1% [20], leading to a greater efficiency in antimicrobial activity through the PDT mechanism than that of the lower N-bonding composition of N-GQDs with a ratio of 2.9% in the N 1–C 1s as well as the N-free GQDs.

For the N-GQDs, surface groups may contribute to a phenomenon associated with intrinsic- and defective-state emission, possibly involving a PL mechanism [19,33,34]. By integrating N-GQDs with dual modality, PDT, and imaging capabilities, high potential was demonstrated for simultaneous PDT elimination of bacteria and tracking of targeted bacteria for evaluating therapeutic effects. In this study, the relative PL QY of the N-GQDs (5.1%) was calculated to be approximately 0.253 (QY of Cy5.5 in DMSO as a reference [24] (SI, Table S6)). Additionally, a similar value for the absolute PL QY [25] of N-GQDs (5.1%) was approximately 0.259, showing a higher relative or absolute PL QY than the N-GQDs (2.9%) and N-free GQDs. Fig. S4b (SI) indicates that the PL spectrum of the N-GQDs (5.1%) strongly emitted at 728 nm in the NIR region, as determined using a PL spectrometer (Ex: 670 nm). Moreover, the photoexcited N-GQDs (5.1%) exhibited higher photostability than did the other conventional PSs (SI, Fig. S15), leading to a reduced photobleaching effect. The laser-treated E. coli alone evidenced no emitted luminescence (Fig. 7
                     a). When irradiation was introduced, the nanomaterial–AbLPS on the bacterial surface started to emit luminescence (Fig. 7b), resulting in a clear image and localization of bacteria, as well as the enhanced specificity and selectivity by the bound AbLPS antibody. After increasing irradiation time to 3 min, the bacteria exhibited severe damage in morphology and surrounding biological substrates on the bacterial surface were oxidized and deteriorated by the generated ROS, leading to desorption of nanomaterial from the bacterial surface and causing decreased luminescence, consistent with the image in Fig. 6d, and forming an aggregated object through the interaction between the debris of destroyed bacteria and nanomaterial–AbLPS (Fig. 7c). According to these results, an N-GQD could potentially serve as a promising contrast probe to track and localize nanomaterial-treated bacteria and provide additional data on the irradiated bacterial status following laser exposure. In addition, the surviving viability of E. coli was indicated by fluorescence and quantification (Fig. 8
                     ) [18–20]. The photoexcited bacteria alone showed nearly no damage, as evidenced by the green fluorescence, indicating live bacteria (Fig. 8a); the dead bacteria from the N-GQD (5.1%)–AbLPS treatments and laser exposure were distinguishable to a particular degree, as indicated by the red fluorescence (Fig. 8b). The viability of bacteria was quantified for additional antimicrobial tests, which showed nearly all nanomaterial-treated bacteria to be dead after treatment (Fig. 8c). Similar viability was quantified through the CFU counting method (Fig. 4) to determine the efficient antibacterial effects of N-GQDs (5.1%) in PDT.
